h, Devon, England":"Lustleigh, Devon, England"},"en":{"Abt 1230–":"about 1230–Deceased","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1270–1298":"1270–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","Abt 1230":"about 1230","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","Church of Saint John the Baptist, Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Lustleigh, Devon, England":"Lustleigh, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coult","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English  <i>colt</i> ‘young horse or ass’, used for a young man or someone thought to resemble a colt in some way, or perhaps for a keeper of colts;  compare  Coltman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colt","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>colt</i> ‘young ass or horse’, probably for a lively, perhaps sexually unrestrained, young man.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Poulin   ‘young animal, colt’.","History: Pierre Poulin alias Peter Colt, born in 1818 in Trois-Rivières, QC, was a son of Augustin Guillaumme Poulin . He married Genevieve Dastromp (Destromp) in 1843 in Sherbrooke, QC."]},{"name":"Coltman","meanings":["English: occupational name for someone who looked after asses and horses, from Middle English <i>colt</i> ‘young ass’ + <i>man</i>. See   Colt  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Coult was born about 1230, in Lustleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with William De Wadham IV."},"et":{"Abt 1230–":"umbes 1230–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1270–1298":"1270–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","Abt 1230":"umbes 1230","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","Church of Saint John the Baptist, Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lustleigh, Devon, England":"Lustleigh, Devon, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1230–":"noin 1230–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1270–1298":"1270–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","Abt 1230":"noin 1230","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","Church of Saint John the Baptist, Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lustleigh, Devon, England":"Lustleigh, Devon, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1230–":"environ 1230–Décédée","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1270–1298":"1270–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Décédée","Abt 1230":"environ 1230","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","Church of Saint John the Baptist, Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lustleigh, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lustleigh, Devon, England":"Lustleigh, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Coult est née environ 1230, à Lustleigh, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec William De Wadham IV."},"de":{"Abt 1230–":"um 1230–Verstorben","1230–Male":"1230–Verstorben","1270–1298":"1270–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Verstorben","Abt 1230":"um 1230","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","Church of Saint John the Baptist, Lustleigh, Teignbridge district, Devonsh